   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "##  Part 1 \u2014 Basic Exploration\n",
    "\n",
    "Before diving into analysis, we get a high-level feel for the dataset:\n",
    "- How large is it?\n",
    "- What time range does it cover?\n",
    "- How many nations are represented?\n",
    "- Who plays at home the most?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "14dcb7d5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Question 1 \u2014 How many matches are in the dataset?\n",
    "\n",
    "`df.shape` returns a tuple `(rows, columns)`.  \n",
    "Each row represents one match, so `df.shape[0]` gives the total number of matches."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "d7cb0a1d",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
   ],
   "source": [
    "total_matches = df.shape[0]\n",
    "total_columns = df.shape[1]\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Total matches (rows)   : {total_matches:,}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Total features (columns): {total_columns}\")\n",
    "print(f\"\\nColumn names: {list(df.columns)}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "44a93aaf",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Question 2 \u2014 What is the earliest and latest year in the data?\n",
    "\n",
    "The `date` column is stored as a string like `'1872-11-30'`.  \n",
    "We convert it to a proper `datetime` object using `pd.to_datetime()`, then extract the **year** with `.dt.year`.  \n",
    "`.min()` and `.max()` give us the date range."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "c38b8397",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Convert 'date' column to datetime for proper comparison\n",
    "df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date'])\n",
    "\n",
    "earliest = df['date'].min()\n",
    "latest   = df['date'].max()\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Earliest match : {earliest.strftime('%B %d, %Y')}  (Year {earliest.year})\")\n",
    "print(f\"Latest match   : {latest.strftime('%B %d, %Y')}  (Year {latest.year})\")\n",
    "print(f\"Data spans     : {latest.year - earliest.year} years\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b869fbe4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Question 3 \u2014 How many unique countries are there?\n",
    "\n",
    "A country can appear as either a **home team** or an **away team**.  \n",
    "We use `pd.concat()` to combine both columns into one Series, then call `.nunique()` to count distinct values.\n",
    "\n",
    "> Using a **set union** via `pd.concat` is more robust than checking either column alone \u2014 it captures every nation that has ever played internationally."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "d2871876",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
   
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Combine home and away team columns and count unique names\n",
    "all_teams = pd.concat([df['home_team'], df['away_team']])\n",
    "unique_countries = all_teams.nunique()\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Unique nations that have played internationally: {unique_countries}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Bonus: show a few examples\n",
    "print(f\"\\nSample nations: {sorted(all_teams.unique())[:10]} ...\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e3299737",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Question 4 \u2014 Which team appears most frequently as home team?\n",
    "\n",
    "`df['home_team'].value_counts()` counts how many times each team name appears in the `home_team` column and **sorts** from most to least frequent.  \n",
    "`.head(10)` shows the top-10 most frequent home teams."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "b54d3243",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    
   ],
   "source": [
    "home_freq = df['home_team'].value_counts()\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Top 10 most frequent home teams:\")\n",
    "print(home_freq.head(10).to_string())\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"\\n Most frequent home team: '{home_freq.index[0]}' with {home_freq.iloc[0]:,} home matches\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "06d75382",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
